          "None Specified",
          "[45 Behavioral Features, Gender and Provenience]",
          "Authors created a nomenclature for different types of students based on the difference between confidence in prediction and actual label: \n\nKnown knowns: Model is very confident and prediction matches label.\n\nKnown unknowns: Low condfidence prediction.\n\nUnknown Unknowns: High confidence prediction of incorrect label. \n\nBased on this observation, the authors create different prediction models and try to characterize the different groups.",
          "BiLSTM, Random Forest",
          "-",
          "-",
          "Flipped Classroom models have a higher percentage of Unknowns that MOOC models. With RF being better at identifying them.\n\nHowever, MMOOCs also exhibit the existence of Unknowns. \n\nWhen characterizing Unknowns Unknowns in a Flipped Classroom setting… the authors identify multiple variables associated with frequency and engagement as relevant for the prediction.",
          "Scientific: \n\nData is partial in nature and does not capture all student behavior. So, having a model only assess performance based on accuracy may lead to misleading results.\n\nTechniological: \n\nNeed for better ways of identifying unknown unknowns since the current models struggle with them.\n\nSocial:\n\nNeed to introduce interpretability for trust in implementation. ",
